## Permission bootstrap checklist (per package)

Defining scopes alone does **not** make a package's permissions functional. A package is permission-complete only when **all** of the following artifacts exist. Scopes without access groups means no assignable roles; access groups without document access wiring means documents are invisible or locked to their creator; API handlers without `@RequirePermission` means actions are ungated.

### Required artifacts (in order)

| # | Artifact | Where | Why |
|---|----------|-------|-----|
| 1 | **Permission scopes** | `<concept>/shared/src/main/permission-scope.ts` | Define what actions exist (view, create, etc.) |
| 2 | **Access groups with hierarchy** | `<concept>/shared/src/main/access-groups.ts` | Define assignable roles (Read, Write, Admin) that grant scopes. Use `memberKeys` to chain groups so higher roles inherit lower ones. |
| 3 | **Group IDs for document access** | Same file, exported constants | `hashToUniqueId<DatabaseDef_AccessGroup["dbKey"]>('group/<key>')` — these are used by the document access wiring to stamp `__access` on new documents. |
| 4 | **`@RequirePermission` on API handlers** | `<concept>/backend/src/main/` on relevant modules | Gate actions so only callers with the right scope can invoke them. |
| 5 | **Document access wiring** | `<concept>/backend/src/main/<concept>-access-wiring.ts` | Call `ModuleBE_Permissions.setAccessContextResolver` for every DB module the package owns. Without this, new documents get only the creator's personal access group — other users and automated flows cannot read/write them. |
| 6 | **Call the wiring function** | App backend init (e.g. module `init()` or app-level setup) | The wiring function from step 5 must be **called** during app initialization — creating and exporting it is not enough. Find where analogous wiring functions are invoked (e.g. `wireYoutubeDocumentAccess()`) and add the new call alongside them. |
| 7 | **Service account** (if automated operations exist) | Scope ID in `permission-scope.ts`, SA group ID in `access-groups.ts` | Packages with scheduled/automated operations (polling, syncing, background processing) need a service account so those operations run with proper permissions. Without an SA, automated flows either fail or depend on whichever user triggered them. |
| 8 | **Exports** | `<concept>/shared/src/main/index.ts`, `<concept>/backend/src/main/index.ts` | All scopes, access groups, group IDs, and wiring functions must be exported from their package's public surface. |

### Group hierarchy pattern

Follow the Read → Write → Delete → Admin pattern with `memberKeys` chaining:

```
Admin (top) — memberKeys: ['<domain>-admin'] or domain parent
  ├── Delete — memberKeys: ['<domain>-admin']
  ├── Write — memberKeys: ['<domain>-admin'], scopes: [entity:create, ...]
  └── Read — memberKeys: ['<domain>-admin'], scopes: [ui:view]
```

Admin inherits all lower groups via membership. A user added to Write automatically gets Read-level access because Write's `memberKeys` includes Admin, and Admin includes Read. Assign a user to the lowest group that covers their needs.

### Canonical example

`market/youtube/sampler` is the reference implementation:

- `shared/src/main/permission-scope.ts` — 10 scopes + service account ID
- `shared/src/main/access-groups.ts` — full group hierarchy (Content Read/Write/Delete/Admin, Sampling Read/Write/Delete/Admin, Domain Admin) with `memberKeys` chaining and exported group IDs
- `backend/src/main/youtube-access-wiring.ts` — `wireYoutubeDocumentAccess()` calling `setAccessContextResolver` for every DB module

### Warning

If a package defines scopes but skips steps 2–6, the result is:

- **No assignable roles** — admins cannot grant users access through the Permissions UI because there are no groups to add them to.
- **Invisible documents** — without custom access wiring, new documents are stamped with only the creator's personal group. Other users cannot query, write, or delete them.
- **Ungated APIs** — without `@RequirePermission`, any authenticated user can call any API handler.
- **Broken automation** — without a service account, automated backend operations have no permission context and will fail or behave unpredictably.

